
Problem Understanding

The goal of this project was to simulate a transaction reconciliation system between:

Platform Transactions (Internal records)
Bank Settlements (External records)

The objective was to identify mismatches and anomalies between these two datasets.

Key Issues to Detect

The reconciliation system was designed to detect the following anomalies:

Settlement recorded in the next month
Rounding differences in amounts
Duplicate settlement entries
Refunds without matching transactions
Missing settlement records
Approach

The project was developed step-by-step using the following approach:

Step 1 — Generate Synthetic Transaction Dataset

Created a dataset of 50 platform transactions including:

Transaction ID
Transaction Date
Amount
Transaction Type

Used NumPy to generate random values for realism.

Step 2 — Generate Settlement Dataset

Created a bank settlement dataset with:

Settlement delays of 1–2 days
Matching transaction IDs
Corresponding amounts

This simulated real-world settlement behavior.

Step 3 — Introduce Intentional Discrepancies

To test the reconciliation logic, intentional anomalies were introduced:

One settlement moved to next month
One rounding mismatch added (+0.01)
One duplicate settlement entry
One refund without matching transaction
Step 4 — Data Cleaning & Preparation
Converted date columns to datetime format
Identified duplicate records
Removed duplicates for clean reconciliation
Step 5 — Merge Datasets

Used Outer Join to compare:

Platform Transactions
Bank Settlements

This allowed detection of:

Missing records
Extra records
Mismatches
Step 6 — Reconciliation Logic

Implemented logic to detect:

Missing bank settlement
No matching transaction
Amount mismatch
Settlement in next month

Each issue was stored in a structured issues dataframe.

Step 7 — Generate Summary Report

The system outputs:

Issues found
Duplicate entries
Total transactions
Total settlements
Issue breakdown
